Finding The Winning Formula: Examining NFL Positional Spending and Success Rates¶

By Noel Edah, Jordan Johnson, and Matt Gordon

Motivation¶

The NFL is one of the most popular and lucrative sports leagues in the world with its popularity and profitability only increasing with each passing year. This explosion in profitability is resulting in players signing bigger contracts each year. As player contracts get larger, it becomes more important to spend this money prudently, to get the most bang for your buck. This careful thought into NFL spending can be seen in many ways such as the devaluing of positions like running back. This begs the question: which positions are most important for winning? Or, what is the best allocation of spending on each position group to optimize winning?

In this project, we will look at NFL teams positional spending data from the last 10 NFL seasons (2013-2022) to try and answer this question

Part 1: Data Collection, Parsing, and Cleaning¶

In this part of the data science lifecycle, we are going to collect our data. We'll begin by scraping NFL positional spending data from overthecap.com. They provide a positional spending table for each team, each year from 2013-2022. Since we eventually want to analyze the time frame as a whole, we need to loop through these tables and concatenate them into one big dataframe with a new observation to specify which year the row is from.

Once we clean the dataframe with all of our positional spending data, we need to then scrape a table from the internet to get the win percentages of each team from 2013-2022 and add it to our existing dataframe.

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import warnings
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy import stats
import seaborn as sns
import sklearn

# Suppress FutureWarning messages
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=FutureWarning)

# url of the tables we want
url = 'https://overthecap.com/positional-spending'

# using requests.get to store the html
html = requests.get(url).text

# using beautiful soup to clean up the html
soup = BeautifulSoup(html, 'html.parser')
BeautifulSoup = soup.prettify()

# using find_all to extract all the tables from the html
tables = soup.find_all('table')

# Now using pandas to get a list of dataframes, each dataframe is one of the yearly tables
table_dfs = pd.read_html(str(tables))

# Empty list we will populate with the dataframes after we add a year column
dfs = []

# List of years we will use to populate the year column
years = ['2013', '2014', '2015', '2016', '2017', '2018', '2019', '2020', '2021', '2022']

# Looping through each dataframe, adding a year column, and appending to dfs
for i in range(0, 10): 
  tmp_df = table_dfs[i]
  tmp_df['Year'] = years[i]
  dfs.append(tmp_df)

# concatenating all of the dataframes together
df = pd.concat(dfs)

# Reset indices 
df = df.reset_index(drop=True)
 
# Reordering the columns
cols = ['Team', 'Year', 'QB', 'RB', 'WR', 'TE', 'OL', 'IDL', 'EDGE', 'LB', 'S', 'CB', 'Offense', 'Defense']
df = df.reindex(columns=cols)

In [ ]:
# empty list to hold the win pct tables we get from each year
dfs = []

# iterating for 10 years and scraping a different url corresponding to the year each iteration
for i in range(0, 10): 
  url = 'https://betiq.teamrankings.com/nfl/betting-trends/win-loss-records/?season=' + str(years[i])
  tmp_df = pd.read_html(url)[0]

  # Add year column
  tmp_df['Year'] = years[i]

  # drop unwanted columns
  tmp_df = tmp_df.drop(columns=['Win-Loss Record', 'MOV', 'ATS +/-'])

  # Add this year's df to the list
  dfs.append(tmp_df)

# Concatenate the dataframes and reindex
winpct_df = pd.concat(dfs)
winpct_df  = winpct_df.reindex(columns=['Team', 'Year', 'Win %'])

# Converting the percentages to floats
winpct_df['Win %'] = winpct_df['Win %'].str.replace('%', '').astype(float)

# Show result

Part 2 - Data Visualization & Exploratory Analysis¶

In this part of the data science lifecycle, begin to look for trends in the data we collected. The first trend of interest is the change in spending from 2013 to 2023. To observe this change, we plotted every teams salary in every year in a scatter plot and also plotted the trend line in red. The graph below shows that there has been a significant increase in spending from 2013 to 2023.

In [ ]:
x = df['Year'].astype(int)
y = df['Total Spent']
plt.scatter(x, y)
res = stats.linregress(x,y)
plt.plot(x, res.intercept + res.slope*x, 'r', label='fitted line')
plt.title("Total Expenditure over the Years in the NFL")
plt.xlabel("years")
plt.ylabel("Money Spent in Hundreds of Millions")
plt.show
Out[ ]:
<function matplotlib.pyplot.show(close=None, block=None)>

Next we wanted to observe the distrubution of how each position is paid throughout the league. To do this, we constructed a violin plot with the positions along the x-axis and the percentage of the salary along the y-axis. This graph shows us that the offensive and defensive side of the ball are paid about equally. It also shows us that there seems to be two strategies in paying Quarterbacks as exemplified by their bimodality. In one camp, you pay them very little around 5% of your total expenditure. QBs in this camp are possibly on their rookie contract. In the other camp, you pay them much more, around 15% of your total expenditure. These QBs are likely more proven and have earned this money from their respective clubs. There are few teams that spend in that middle ground, around 10%.

For other position groups, the distributions are unimodal. Less than 5% of total expenditure goes to RB and TE. WRs make about 10% of total expenditure along with the defensive line, both interior and edge. Linebackers and safeties both tend to make up below 10% of total salary and cornerbacks tend to make up a little bit above 10% of total salary. The offensive lineman are typically the priciest item on an owners ledger in terms of the roster coming in at just under 20% of the cap.

The bar graphs below are just another way to see how spending differs across the league. For each year, each teams expenditure was plotted as a bar graph of different colors representing expenditure on different position groups. This goes to show you that there are different strategies in spending across the league.

In [ ]:
for x in years:
  #isolate data for specific years and drop unnecessary columns
  data = df[df['Year'] == x]
  data = data.drop(columns=['Year', 'Offense %', 'Defense %', 'Total Spent', 'Win %'])

  # create figure for current year
  plt.figure(figsize=(13,6))

  # create input of average team spending for current year and add to data
  avg = {'Team':'Average', 'QB %':data['QB %'].mean(), 'RB %':data['RB %'].mean(), 'WR %':data['WR %'].mean(), 'TE %':data['TE %'].mean(), 'OL %':data['OL %'].mean(), 'IDL %':data['IDL %'].mean(), 'EDGE %':data['EDGE %'].mean(), 'LB %':data['LB %'].mean(), 'S %':data['S %'].mean(), 'CB %':data['CB %'].mean()} 
  data = data.append(avg, ignore_index=True)

  # labels & titles for the plot
  plt.title("Allocation of Salary for Each Team in " + x)
  plt.xlabel("Teams")
  plt.ylabel("Percentage of Expenditure")

  #rotate team names and make it so the bars are stacked on top of each other
  plt.xticks(rotation=90)
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on QB")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['RB %'], bottom=data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on RB")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['WR %'], bottom=data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on WR")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['TE %'], bottom=data['WR %']+data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on TE")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['OL %'], bottom=data['TE %']+data['WR %']+data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on OL")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['IDL %'], bottom=data['OL %']+data['TE %']+data['WR %']+data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on IDL")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['EDGE %'], bottom=data['IDL %']+data['OL %']+data['TE %']+data['WR %']+data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on EDGE")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['LB %'], bottom=data['EDGE %']+data['IDL %']+data['OL %']+data['TE %']+data['WR %']+data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on LB")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['S %'], bottom=data['LB %']+data['EDGE %']+data['IDL %']+data['OL %']+data['TE %']+data['WR %']+data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on S")
  plt.bar(data['Team'], data['CB %'], bottom=data['S %']+data['LB %']+data['EDGE %']+data['IDL %']+data['OL %']+data['TE %']+data['WR %']+data['RB %']+data['QB %'], label="Percentage spent on CB")
  plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1.0), loc='upper left')

Now onto the interesting stuff. Much has been made about the "rookie QB window" in the NFL. The rookie QB window theory suggests that the best time for a team to win is in a QBs rookie contract becuase productive QBs on rookie deals allow you to spend big elsewhere. Is this theory correct? Is there any position where being relatively cheap in your expenditure is correlated with success?

To answer these questions, we made scatter plots for each of the positions and plotted win percentage as a function of percentage of salary spent on that position. If the rookie QB theory is true, then we'd expect to see a negative trend in this scatter plot for QBs.

In [ ]:
temp_df = df.drop(columns=['Team', 'Year', 'Total Spent', 'Win %'])
positions = temp_df.columns
# plot percentage of total expenditure against win percentage for each position
for pos in positions:
  plt.figure()
  plt.scatter(df[pos], df['Win %'])
  plt.title(pos + " vs. Win Percentage")
  plt.xlabel("Percentage of Total Expenditure")
  plt.ylabel("Win Percentage")
  res = stats.linregress(df[pos], df['Win %'])
  plt.plot(df[pos], res.intercept + res.slope*df[pos], 'r', label='fitted line')
  plt.show()

These graphs suggest that the rookie QB window theory is not true. As stated above, if the theory was true, we'd expect to see a negative slope of the trend line in the QB scatter plot. What we actually observed was the opposite, a slight positive slope for the trendline, although the data obviously does not fit the trendline very well.

For all the other positions a similar story was told: the trendlines were not much different from horizontal lines, indicating little to no trend in the data and the trend line did not fit the data very well. This does not bode well for being able to establish a winning formula from this data.

Residual plot analysis¶

The fact that the violin plot is symmetrical around zero indicates that the residuals follow a symmetric distribution. This suggests that the errors in your model are distributed evenly on both sides of zero, indicating a lack of bias in the predictions.This indicates that the model is capturing the general trend and patterns in the data reasonably well.

As a last resort, we attempted to predict the win percentage of nfl teams using scikit learns MLPRegressor model. This model implements a Multi-Layer Perceptron to predict continuous values. The loss function it uses is squared error and it uses ReLu as the activation function. The activation function is important because it adds some nonlinearity to the model, allowing it to represent relationships that simple regressions like the ones above can't. The loss function provides a mean to assess the performance of the model. The solver is set as 'lbgfs' because the scikit learn specs say that lbgfs is best for working with small datasets like we're working with here.

We start by setting aside a small portion of the data to test the model with and removing it from the training pool. It is important not to train on the test data because you want to see how your model responds to new data. We chose to sample 10% or about 32 samples to test with later. The next steps were to drop the win %, year, and team from both the testing and training data. We don't want our model to take any of that information into account. From there, we then scaled the data using scikit learn because MLPs are sensitive to scaled features and scaling the data should result in improved performance. We also decreased the size of the hidden layer from the default of 100 to two layers of 4 and 3 nodes complexity to try and improve performance.

Even with these adjustments, we struggled to fit a model that's performance was much better than a horizontal line. In many instances of training the model, the model was actually worse than a horizintal line.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPRegressor
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# sample 10% of total datapoints for testing
test = df.sample(frac=0.1)
train = df

# drop testing data from training data
for ind in test.index:
  train = train.drop(index=ind)
  
# seperate the win percentage (value to predict) from the salary data and drop \
# unnecessary columns
train_y = train['Win %']
train_x = train.drop(columns=['Win %', 'Team', 'Year'])
test_y = test['Win %']
test_x = test.drop(columns=['Win %', 'Team', 'Year'])

#create scaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(train_x.values)

#scale data
train_x = scaler.transform(train_x.values)
test_x = scaler.transform(test_x.values)

#create MLPRegressor and obtain R^2 (score)
reg = MLPRegressor(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=5000, hidden_layer_sizes=[4, 3])
reg.fit(train_x, train_y)
pred = reg.predict(test_x)
reg.score(test_x, test_y)

Part 5 - Insight and Policy Decision¶

Unfortunately, we were not able to elucidate the relationship between positional spending and win percentage in this notebook. We tried three different models here: a linear regression including just the percentage of salary spent on offense and defense, a linear regression including the percentage of salary spent on individual positions/position groups (not offense and defense), and a MLPRegressor including the percentage of salary spent on individual positions/position groups. None of these models yielded data that fit the data as seen by very low r^2 values, but from the first regression we were able to see that a relationship does exist between the percentage of salary spent on offense and defense and win percentage. Further analysis is required to determine the exact relationship and build models that will be useful in determining which players to pay and how much.

Ideally this analysis would be done with more data than we had. We were only able to find salary data going back to 2013, giving us about 320 datapoints to train and test models on, which is not a lot. More training examples would help improve our poor performance.
